        introduction: "Poissy is a town of 40,000 in the Yvelines, steeped in history and undergoing transformation. The baptism place of King Saint Louis in 1214, the town preserves the magnificent Collégiale Notre-Dame, a 12th-century Romanesque and Gothic church housing the baptismal font where the future Louis IX was christened. Villa Savoye, Le Corbusier's 1931 masterpiece, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of modern architecture's most accomplished manifestos — its pilotis, roof terrace and ribbon windows revolutionised 20th-century architecture. Poissy's industrial history is marked by the car factory established in 1938, successively Simca, Chrysler, Talbot then PSA, now Stellantis, still employing thousands and producing Peugeot 208 and 2008 models. The Meissonier park along the Seine offers 43 hectares of green space with an 18-hole golf course. The market, founded by a 1221 charter, runs Tuesdays, Fridays and Sundays on Place de la République.",
        itineraire: "From Paris, your TaxiNeo driver takes the western ring road then the A14 motorway towards Orgeval-Rouen. The toll A14 (about €3.60) passes through the La Défense and Nanterre tunnels before emerging onto the Chambourcy plain. The Poissy exit (exit 7) leads to boulevard Robespierre down to the town centre and the Seine. For Villa Savoye, the driver takes rue de Villiers northward — the villa is at number 82. A free alternative via the A86 then RD308 through Chatou and Le Vésinet adds 10 minutes but is toll-free and pleasant along the Seine.",
